📄 Recent arXiv Papers (2025–2026)

1. Mechanical Enforcement for LLM Governance: Evidence of Governance-Task Decoupling in Financial Decision Systems
Authors: José Manuel de la Chica Rodríguez, Carlos Martí-González

Date: May 2026

Link: [arXiv:2605.14744](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2605.14744v1)

Why it matters: This paper exposes a critical flaw in how banks govern LLMs. Under "text-only governance" (where the model itself interprets compliance policies), 27% of deferrals carry no decision-relevant information. The authors propose mechanical enforcement — four primitives operating outside the model's interpretive loop — which reduces this by 73% and raises task accuracy from MCC 0.43 to 0.88.

For your team: If your compliance chatbot or decision-support LLM is self-interpreting policies, this paper argues you're doing governance wrong. The architecture matters more than the prompt.

---

2. A Regulatory Governance Framework for AI-Driven Financial Fraud Detection in U.S. Banking
Author: Mohammad Nasir Uddin

Date: April 2026

Link: [arXiv:2605.04076](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2605.04076v1)

Why it matters: The first integrated deployment blueprint that simultaneously satisfies OCC Bulletin 2011-12, SR 11-7, CFPB AI circular, and FinCEN BSA/SAR requirements. It proposes an RDT-FG Regulatory Digital Twin that translates model metrics into four regulator-specific health scores and a composite Regulatory Fitness Index. Benchmarked on IEEE-CIS and ULB datasets with an LSTM+XGBoost ensemble (ROC-AUC 0.9289).

For your team: If you're building fraud detection models, this gives you a concrete compliance architecture mapped to actual U.S. regulatory requirements — not just principles.

---

3. LLM Output Drift: Cross-Provider Validation & Mitigation for Financial Workflows
Authors: Raffi Khatchadourian, Rolando Franco

Date: November 2025

Link: [arXiv:2511.07585](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.07585v1)

Why it matters: LLMs in production exhibit nondeterministic output drift that undermines auditability. The study tested five models (7B–120B parameters) and found a stark inverse relationship: smaller models (Granite-3-8B, Qwen2.5-7B) achieve 100% output consistency at T=0.0, while GPT-OSS-120B achieves only 12.5%. They propose a three-tier model classification system and an audit-ready attestation framework mapped to FSB, BIS, and CFTC requirements.

For your team: If you're deploying LLMs for reconciliations, regulatory reporting, or client communications, this paper gives you a deterministic test harness and a framework for risk-appropriate deployment decisions.

---

4. Banking Done Right: Redefining Retail Banking with Language-Centric AI
Authors: Xin Jie Chua et al.

Date: October 2025

Link: [arXiv:2510.07645](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.07645v1)

Why it matters: Describes Ryt AI, the first globally regulator-approved deployment where conversational AI functions as the primary banking interface (not just advisory). Built on an in-house LLM (ILMU) with four specialized agents (Guardrails, Intent, Payment, FAQ), each using task-specific LoRA adapters. Features deterministic guardrails, human-in-the-loop confirmation, and a stateless audit architecture.

For your team: A real-world case study of how to get a regulator to sign off on an LLM-native banking system. The architecture — especially the stateless audit trail and agent specialization — is directly transferable to compliance workflows.

