6. Generative AI in Financial Institution: A Global Survey of Opportunities, Threats, and Regulation
Authors: Bikash Saha, Nanda Rani, Sandeep Kumar Shukla

Date: April 2025

Link: [arXiv:2504.21574](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.21574v1)

Why it matters: A comprehensive survey covering GenAI adoption across banks, insurers, asset managers, and fintechs. Covers AI-powered virtual assistants, fraud detection, compliance automation, and emerging threats (AI-generated phishing, deepfake fraud, adversarial attacks). Proposes best practices including explainability techniques, adversarial testing, auditability, and human oversight.

For your team: A solid reference paper to share with stakeholders who need the 30,000-foot view of GenAI risks and regulatory landscape.

---

7. The Limits of AI in Financial Services
Authors: Isabella Loaiza, Roberto Rigobon

Date: March 2025

Link: [arXiv:2503.22035](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.22035v1)

Why it matters: Argues that AI excels at data-driven tasks but fails at small datasets, subjective probabilities, and contexts requiring human judgment. Proposes the EPOCH framework (Empathy, Presence, Opinion, Creativity, Hope) as irreplaceable human capabilities in finance.

For your team: A useful counterweight to AI hype. Good for framing where human-in-the-loop is non-negotiable vs. where automation is appropriate.

